{"id": "577d0c458c4241ffae5e76166b9360d7", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 23:07:17", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The proposed research direction represents a novel intersection of efficient deep learning, neural architecture search, and representation learning, with a clear focus on addressing the underexplored problem of *dimensional redundancy* in 3D convolutions. By treating kernel dimensionality as a per-channel learnable hyperparameter—guided by semantic priors and optimized via differentiable relaxation—the approach enables fine-grained structural sparsification without sacrificing representational power. The idea of \"dimensional pruning\" is both conceptually innovative and practically impactful, particularly for resource-constrained applications in medical imaging and video understanding. Empirical validation on benchmarks like Something-Something V2 or BraTS will provide essential feedback on feasibility and performance, while allowing parallel development of theoretical insights. Given the maturity of the conceptual framework and the availability of clear technical pathways (e.g., Gumbel-Softmax relaxation, spectral gating, fusion modules), proceeding with implementation ensures timely progress and facilitates real-world impact.\n\nTopic: ```json{\"Selected Topic\": \"AdaKernel-3D: Channel-wise Adaptive 1D/2D/3D Kernel Selection via Dimensional Pruning\"}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "dcc58cf11b5b4bf0ab8f1c84ceb5b53d", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 23:07:21", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "The research topic **AdaKernel-3D: Channel-wise Adaptive 1D/2D/3D Kernel Selection via Dimensional Pruning** has been formally selected. It introduces a novel approach to address *dimensional redundancy* in 3D convolutions by enabling per-channel, learnable kernel dimensionality selection through differentiable relaxation (e.g., Gumbel-Softmax), semantic-aware gating, and fusion strategies. The method aims to achieve fine-grained structural sparsification while preserving representational capacity, with applications in efficient video and medical imaging models. Implementation will proceed immediately to enable empirical validation on benchmarks like Something-Something V2 and BraTS, allowing parallel theoretical development and practical refinement.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
